@node "Versions"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Demo or Registered?"

  			@{b}@{u}DEMONSTRATION OR REGISTERED?@{uu}@{ub}

   A simple  method of  finding out  which  version of  Professional Video 
   Catalogue you have can be  found out by viewing  the "About" box (which
   appears once PVC is loaded.  You can also view this by clicking  on the
   button  marked "A" or select "About" under the "Project" heading in the
   pull down menus. 

@{b}   vX.Xe and VX.Xd  (where X is a number 0 to 9)	(DEMONSTRATIONS)@{ub}
   If your  version  number is  in the format  vX.Xe (eg. v1.0e) or  vX.Xd
   (eg. v1.0d) where X is a number 0 to 9 then you have an EVALUATION/DEMO
   version of  Professional Video Catalogue.  There will also be a mention 
   of  EVALUATION or DEMO somewhere.  If you have  a DEMO version  you may
   freely  distribute the DEMO but only if the terms of license are upheld
   when doing so and are imposed on anyone receipt of said DEMO.

@{b}   vX.Xes						(SPECIAL DEMOS)@{ub}
   There are a limited number of special demonstration versions. These are
   to be  treated  with the  same  approach as  REGISTERED versions.  Such 
   versions only exis t as gifts from  the author  to individuals (to whom
   they are licensed too - see "About" text).  Persons  with  this version 
   will notice NON-DISTRIBUTABLE cropping up all over the place - remember
   it well.

@{b}   All Other Versions (typically vX.Xr)			(REGISTERED) @{ub}
   If your  version  number is NOT in the format of vX.Xe, vX.Xd or vX.Xes
   then you have a REGISTERED version  of Professional Video Catalogue and
   to prove this your  name and  address will be  present somewhere in the
   "About"  text.  There will  also be a mention  of  it being  REGISTERED 
   somewhere.   Such  a  version   is   copyrighted  and  is  NOT   freely 
   distributable. 

   If you have a registered version but you have not registered, the terms
   of license  granted herein are void. You will also  breaking the law by
   commiting software theft and  breach of copyright.  A part from risking
   prosecution, you will be assisting in the decline of the Amiga which is
   mostly due to the amount of pirates out there. 

   Each registered version  is customised  such that  illegal distribution
   can be easily traced to source. People that offend WILL be black-listed
   from  any  future  product  registrations, WILL  lose  all registration
   status  (ie. no  discounts, no  email  news  letters  etc) and  may  be
   prosecuted for breach of copyright. 

   To paraphrase @{i}"If it's worth using then it's worth paying for"@{ui}.
@endnode
