@node "Introduction"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: What is PVC?"

				@{b}@{u}B. WHAT IS PVC?@{uu}@{ub}

   How many times have you  started to record a film only to find that the
   @$%Ł^ tape runs out in the last 10 minutes of the film?  And those with
   large collections  will know  what it is like trying  to find a film or
   programme amongst the billions of scrawled labels that your baby sister 
   has scribbled crayon on?

   Well, this is where Professional  Video Catalogue (or PVC) steps out of 
   the shadows to save  your sanity as you hunt  aimlessly for "Neighbours
   and Keeping them Away" tape  (a prime target for  erasal if anyone else
   should find it).

   So how does this latter day white knight help? PVC allows you to keep a
   record of  what's on each video,  how long each entry is,  what channel 
   recordings are made from etc.  Obviously,  the more data  you give PVC,
   the more you'll  get out of using it.  PVC will even  estimate how much
   space is left  on a tape and  attempt to  calculate the  amount of tape
   gained when  leaving out adverts  (it's amazing  what a difference this
   makes on 8 hours of long play)!

   In short, PVC is an invaluable tool for  maintaining your collection of
   videos (or anything else that is recorded).
@endnode
@node "Installation"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Installation"

				@{b}@{u}C. INSTALLATION@{uu}@{ub}

   Readers of novice AND expert  knowledge about the amiga should read the
   following text to ensure a fully working installation:-

	@{" Demonstration/Special versions " link "InstallDemo"}	Worth a look even for REGISTERED users
	@{" Full Registered version        " link "InstallRegistered"}	Demo users need not apply
@endnode
@node "InstallDemo"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Demo Installation"

  				@{u}DEMONSTRATION INSTALLATION@{uu}  

   You MUST have the following programs for PVC (demo) to function:

		PVC			(This may be renamed)
		PVC.guide		(May NOT be renamed)
		
   To install simply type the following:-

	ASSIGN PVC: <path1>	
		;Where <path1> is the desired location for PVC

	LHARC X <path2>/PRVIDEOC.LHA PVC:
		;Where <path2> is the current location for the PVC archive

   NB. PVC executable may be anywhere.
       PVC:PVC.Guide must exist for your version to run!

   @{u}The Author advises@{uu} (any REGISTERED users reading may ignore this)

   * OS3.0+ users should attempt to ensure the existance of:-

			 SYS:UTILITIES/MULTIVIEW

   * Other users should obtain the AMIGAGUIDEź distribution available from
     AmiNet. Follow the directions for installation and type:-

		RENAME AMIGAGUIDE SYS:UTILITIES/MULTIVIEW
		COPY AMIGAGUIDE.LIBRARY LIBS:
@endnode
@node "InstallRegistered"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Registered Installation"

	   			@{u}REGISTERED INSTALLATION@{uu}

   To install PVC (REGISTERED):-

	LHARC X <path2>/PRVIDEOC.LHA <path2>
		; Where <path1> is the current location for the PVC archive
		; And where <path2> is the place you want PVCs system files

   You may assign PVC: to <path2> (see above).

   Alternatively,  you  can  run  PVC1_0r (see  below),  ignore  all  error
   messages and :-

	Select SET PREFS under the PREFS heading from the pull down menu.
	Select SEL next under the PVC PATH  heading hand a file requester
	   will appear.
        Select any file from the PVC path (same as <path1>).
        Select OK  on the file  requester  and click USE (bottom left) on
	   the Config/prefs window. 
	Select SAVE DEFAULT PREFS from  the PREFS menu.  This will create
	    S:PVC.PREFS

   This sounds very  complicated but is very  simple in practise.  If you
   experience  any  problems  temporarily  assign PVC:  to  the  path  of 
   PVC_samples.abk .

   SET PREFS allows you  to configure what text viewer you would  like to
   read  this document  with first,  which ProTracker module  you want to 
   play, the name of this file and  the accompanying readme file and much
   more besides. Play around  with it (the SET PREFS option!) until  your
   happy with things, but don't forget to save your options.

   Please see @{" Set Prefs " link "SetPrefs"} for more on it's operation.


   @{u}Things to Note@{uu}

   If you're like me, you will hate programs that create files all over 
   the &!**@% place. So rather than let you wake up one dreary morning
   and find rogue files littering your disk(s) i'm gonna tell ya...

		S:PVC.prefs		Preferences/Config file
		
   And that's it! The rest of 'em are entirely upto you.

   @{u}Default Configuration@{uu}

	LastVideo=999		Ż|  These  may need  to be reduced  if 
	LastFilm=99		-+- you keep getting the out of memory 
	LastMisc=25		_|  "Invalid function call" errors.
	VideoLen=240
	AdvertLen=4
	AdFreqTol=34
	PVCpath=PVC:
	DatFile=PVC:VidList
	HelpFile=PVC:PVC.guide
	NewsFile=PVC:PVC_ReadMe.guide
	FileView=Sys:utilities/MultiView
	SongFile=ST-01:mod.protracker
	Sound=Yes
	Blank=60
	TagData=Yes
	Crypt=No		--- This speeds up loading considerably
				    (Encryption is  mind numbingly slow
				    due to AMOS having trouble with the
				    algorithm!)
@endnode
@node "Cycle Button"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Cycle Buttons."

				@{u}CYCLE BUTTONS@{uu}
   
   Cycle buttons appear quite frequently in PVC. The most common graphical
   one contains two or all of the following three states:-

		-	(hyphen)	Don't Care
		
		X	(cross)		Disabled

		./	(tick)		Enabled
		
   If other cycle button types are used, they will be stated.
@endnode
@{"Owned & Locked Videos" link "Video RWD"}
@node "Video RWD"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Owned & Locked Videos."

				@{u}OWNED & LOCKED VIDEOS@{uu}

   Underneath the main selection window,  you will notice a  small line in
   which either  video details,  the selected film or  "Unused video slot"
   can be seen. The colour of this text reflects:-

	Text 		Locked from	Ownership	Read/Write/
	@{u}colour@{uu}		@{u}changes?   @{uu}	@{u}         @{uu}	@{u}Delete access@{uu}

	CYAN		Unlocked	Yours		RWD

	BLUE		Unlocked	Not Yours	R

	PINK		Locked		Yours		R (unlockable)

	RED		Locked		Not Yours	R

   If an owner other than yourself has a password,  then those videos that
   belong to him or  her will have  "**** Video contents are private ****"
   in the first film entry making all films on that video unviewable.

   See also:-
	@{" Function/Amend Video  " link "Amend Video"} for un/locking videos.
	@{" Function/Owners List  " link "Owners List"} for adding new owners.
	@{" Prefs/Set Options     " link "Set Options"} for password setting.
	@{" Prefs/Select Identity " link "Select ID"} for switching to a different user id.
	@{" Security Checks       " link "Security Check"} for loading with an ID.
@endnode
@node "Security Check"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Security Checks."

				 @{u}SECURITY CHECKS@{uu}

   When loading or merging videobases on  REGISTERED  versions a security
   check will appear:-
			 ___________________
	NB. Quit button	|__|Security_Check__|
	   same as Null	|  _______________  |
			| |UseridK	|_| |
			| |UseridL	|#| |
			| |UseridM	|_| |
			| |_____________|_| |
			| |_Password______| |
			|  ____	      ____  |
			| |Null|     | OK | |
			|___________________|

     You will be asked for  an id and a password.  This is so that videos 
     belonging to that  id can be viewed only by  the person knowing  the
     correct password.
     
     If you are new to the system then click on an empty slot (preferably
     the next  available) in  the users table  (displayed at the security 
     check) so that it is highlighted and press return for password. Then
     once you have"logged in", edit the slot you selected naming it using
     @{" Owners List " link "Owners List"} . You may then edit your password with @{" Set Options " link "Set Options"}
     option in the configuration menu.

     An  alternative for  new users just  wishing to  browse is to select
     either "NULL"  or click on  the close gadget.  This will make you an 
     unnamed user with no powers of ownership. 

     For further security,  the whole video base can be encrypted, with a
     second pass  password encryption  taking place  on all  entries that 
     belong to the current owner. BACKUP your videobase first, i'm not to
     sure how it will behave with several people encrypting. 

     NOTE: Encryption slows loading,  merging and saving  operations down
	   to something slower than the average snail. I'm hoping to sort
	   this out in a future version when i've got the time to re-code
	   PVC into C or Blitz Basic  where such  intensive(?)  tasks are
	   better handled (with a 2-pass compiler).
@endnode
