@node "Load"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Load Project."

				  @{u}1.2 LOAD PROJECT@{uu}

   Called from  either the "Load" option of the  Project Menu or from the
   GUI (disk with cyan arrow pointing this <|. 2nd row up, next to NEW):-
				 ________
				|  ____  |
		 		| |    | | 
				|<|+--+| |
		 		| ||__|| |
				|________|

   This option clears the  videobase of all video, film and miscellaneous
   data and  then loads in a selected file.  You may cancel from the file 
   selector, leaving  all data  in  the  state it  was in  prior to  Load
   selection.

   Registered users should read about @{" Security Checks " link "Security Check"} .
@endnode
@node "Merge"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Merge Project."

				  @{u}1.3 MERGE PROJECT@{uu}

   Called from the "Merge" option of the  Project Menu only.

   This option is very  similar to "Load".  However, instead of losing any
   existing data, Merge simply overwrites  the videobase with the contents
   of the file selected with the file selector. This can be particularly
   useful in pooling videobases.

   NOTE: Videos and films are stored positionally. So if film 4 on video 3
   was  Miss N D Marbles "Batty in the Bellfry"  in the file  about  to be
   merged onto  the current videobase,  then that  is what would be  at in 
   film 4 of video 3 reguardless of what was there prior to it!

   You may quit this option by clicking on the "Cancel" button of the file
   selector as with LOAD and SAVE AS.

   Registered users should read about @{" Security Checks " link "Security Check"} .
@endnode
@node "Save"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Save Project."

				  @{u}1.4 SAVE AS PROJECT@{uu}

   Called from the "Save" option of the Project Menu.

   This option stores  all of the data stored  in the videobase to a file,
   the name of which is determined when you load a videobase. 

   This option will not save  a file unless you have made changes  to the 
   videobase. 
@endnode
@node "Save As"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Save Project As."

				 @{u}1.5 SAVE AS PROJECT@{uu}

   Called from  either  the "Save As" option of the  Project Menu or from
   GUI (disk with red arrow pointing this |>, 2nd row up, above "Mobl"):-
				 ________
				|  ____  |
		 		| |    | | 
				||>+--+| |
				| ||__|| |
				|________|

   This option stores  all of the data stored in the videobase to a file,
   the name of  which you will input through  the file selector.  You may 
   quit this option at this point by clicking on "cancel". 

   Once you have selected a file click on "OK" to save (double clicking a
   filename does the same.
@endnode
@node "Print"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Print Project Menu."

				@{u}1.6 PRINT PROJECT MENU@{uu}

				1.6.1. @{" File    " link "File Print"}	(Not Demo)
				1.6.2. @{" Printer " link "Printer Print"}	(Not Demo)
@endnode
@node "File Print"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: File Print Project."

				@{u}1.6.1 FILE PRINT PROJECT@{uu}

   This is a safe way of getting a videobase listing from PVC. Instead of,
   printing  to printer the  list is redirected to a  file preventing  any
   problems that my occur when printers are off-line (hangs).

   This  option also  allows users  without  printers to take  listings to 
   people who have *GRIN*
@endnode
@node "Printer Print"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Print Project."

				@{u}1.6.2 PRINTING PROJECT@{uu}

   This option allows the user to obtain hard copies of the videobase as a
   listing.

   Problems that will often occur (AMOS' fault honest):-
	Hangs your Amiga until printer is on-line.
	Have to wait for videobase to finish printing.

   The solution to the above  is to use the @{" File " link "File Print"} option from the menu.
   Then you can  print your videobase when  and where you are  like (ASCII
   format output see..)
@endnode
@node "About"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: About PVC."

				@{u}1.7 ABOUT BOX@{uu}

   This panel  gives you  information concerning  which   version   of PVC   
   you are using. It is displayed when ever you select Project/About from
   the menus or click on the button marked with a white A (2nd row up, 
   right most column):-
				 ________
				|   __	 |
				|  /  \  |
				| |____| |
				| |    | |
				|________|

   Click here for further information on @{" versions " link "Versions"} .
@endnode
@node "Quit"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Quit PVC."

				@{u}1.8 QUIT PVC@{uu}

   Now why would you want to click on the icon in the very top left of the   
   screen or select Project/Quit from the menu?

   I can understand users of normal EVALUATION versions wanting to because 
   that bright green isn't  exactly conducive  to long term use.  But, the 
   other users... well... i don't know... it's not on them quitting....

   *sigh*

   Anyway, this option returns  you back to where PVC was launch from (and
   hopefully releasing all memory used).
@endnode
@node "Editor Menu"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Editor Menu."

				  @{u}2. EDITOR MENU@{uu}

				2.1. @{" Set Amend   " link "Amend"}
				2.2. @{" Set Remove  " link "Remove"}
				2.3. @{" Set Scale   " link "Scale"}
				2.4. @{" Set A/D Nav " link "Nav"}
@endnode
@node "Amend"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Amend mode."

				@{u}2.1 SET AMEND@{uu}

   Amend mode, selected from Editor/Set Amend/ menu option or clicking  on   
   the button marked "Ins"  (3rd row up, left column),  allows the user to
   define how PVC behaves when it adds videos and films.

   NOTE: The hot keys defined for these modes of operation can be obtained
   from the menu. For mode toggles just press the F-Key with no shift/alt.

   @{U}MENU OPERATION@{uu}

   The following menu options are submenus of Editor/Amend/...

   EDIT/ALTER	See RELEASED part of ICON OPERATION below.

   INSERT	See DEPRESSED part of ICON OPERATION below.

   @{u}ICON OPERATION@{uu}

   The button marked "Ins" (3rd row, left column):-

   RELEASED	This enables editing mode (OVERWRITE). Films can be
		double-clicked on, edited and then updated.

   DEPRESSED	When ever an addition is made they will be inserted into 
		the slot displayed  (video = video number,  film = video
		number and film number),  moving all  subsequent entries
		forward. IN SHORT: it means INSERT.  Double-clicked film
		entries can be edited and then inserted before the entry
		added (useful for copying episode times for serials).

   See	@{" Set A/D Nav " link "Nav"} for modifiers.
	@{" Amend Film  " link "Amend Film"} for film entry process.
	@{" Amend Video " link "Amenu Video"} for video entry process.
	@{" 
@endnode
@node "Remove"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Remove mode."

				@{u}2.2 SET REMOVE@{uu}

   Remove mode, selected from  Editor/Set Remove/  menu option or clicking   
   on the button marked "Del" (3rd row up, right column),  allows the user
   to define how PVC behaves when it deletes videos and films.

   NOTE: The hot keys defined for these modes of operation can be obtained
   from the menu. For mode toggles just press the F-Key with no shift/alt.

   @{u}MENU OPERATION@{uu}

   The following menu options are submenus of Editor/Amend/...

   BLANK	See RELEASED part of ICON OPERATION below.

   DELETE	See DEPRESSED part of ICON OPERATION below.

   @{u}ICON OPERATION@{uu}

   The button marked "Del" (3rd row, right column):-

   RELEASED	This enables  blanking mode.  Any removals  made result in
		the selected film being unallocated.

		If you unallocate the  penultimate film of a video then it
		will be unallocated, but the space will still be taken up.
		You haven't spliced  the film,  just said you can  use the
		space taken up by it for something else. If you now remove
		the last film  both it's film length  and the  unallocated
		film will be erased.

		When removing a video the first click will clear it of all
		films but  leave all video details (ownership, length etc)
		intact.  If there were no films on the  video or remove is
		called a second  time then the  video will  be unallocated 
		of all details (sort of like formating it).

   DEPRESSED	This  enables  delete mode.  Any  removals  result in  all 
                subsequent entries  (video or film  depending on which you
		are removing) being pulled back one slot. 

		To visualize this, go to a Shell and type lots of junk and
		then move to the middle and press the DEL key. See how the
		characters are dragged back.

   See	@{" Set A/D Nav  " link "Nav"} for modifiers.
	@{" Remove Film  " link "Remove Film"} for film removal process.	
	@{" Remove Video " link "Remove Video"} for video removal process.
@endnode
@node "Scale"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Scale Modes."

				@{u}2.3 SCALE MODES@{uu}

   This set of functions simplifies  movement through the videobase by use
   of scale factors.  They only effect  the slider bars on the main screen
   (because they are less necessary on miscellaneous data types).

   NOTE: The hot keys defined for these modes of operation can be obtained
   from the menu. For mode toggles just press the F-Key with no shift/alt.

   @{u}MENU OPERATION@{uu}

   The following menu options are submenus of Editor/Set Scale/ .

   NORMAL	See RELEASED entry in ICON OPERATION (below).

   SCALE	See DEPRESSED entry in ICON OPERATION (below).

   @{u}ICON OPERATION@{uu}

   The button marked "mini" (bottom row, left).

   RELEASED	This is the  system default.  Each position  of the slider
		represents 1/(maximum videos or films depending on slider)
		thus giving an overview of the video base as a whole.

   DEPRESSED	This function  enables a "Mini"  environment;  a magnified 
		slider view so that you only see areas of importance. Each
		position of the slider represents 1/(last entry + 1).
@endnode
@node "Nav"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: A/D Nav Modes."

				@{u}2.4 A/D NAV MODES@{uu}

   This set of functions alters the  way in which all add/delete functions 
   behave in terms of what they do after they have added/deleted. IE. They
   affect whether the relevant interfaces are locked in place for multiple
   add/delete functions. 

   You can tell which  mode of operation is being  used by  inspecting the 
   top right hand corner of main interface:-

   STATIC	One edit, no automatic slot selection (or auto movement).
   MOBILE	Multiple edits, auto movement.

   @{u}MENU OPERATION@{uu}

   The following menu options are submenus of Editor/"Set A/D Nav"/ .

   STATIC	See RELEASED entry in ICON OPERATION (below).

   MOBILE	See DEPRESSED entry in ICON OPERATION (below).

   @{u}ICON OPERATION@{uu}

   The button marked "Mobl" (bottom row, right) for mobile.

   RELEASED	This is the system default. Multiple videobase alterations
		are carried  out  by  repeatedly  selecting  the  required 
		function as explained in:-

		@{" Amend Film " link "Amend Film"} , @{" Amend Video " link "Amenu Video"} , @{" Remove Film " link "Remove Film"} and @{" Remove Video " link "Remove Video"}

   DEPRESSED	Below  are  listed  the  affects  obtainable  with  "Mobl"
		depressed:-

	VIEWPORT CONTROL
		Moving between videos no  longer resets so that film 01 is
		visible   (ie. the viewport is completely  under the users 
		control!).
		
	ADDING WITH INS RELEASED ("Quit" button exits)
		Interface does  not vanish.  Ideal if adding several slots
		(film or video)  that  are not  contiguous  (one after the
		other).  Note:  All additions  require  the user  to input
		any  positional information  (video "Number", "Next"  film
		etc.)
		 
	ADDING WITH INS DEPRESSED ("Quit" button exits)
		Interface  does not  vanish,  but  unlike above  contigous
		entries  can be  made quickly  by clicking  on the  button
		marked "OK" (1 click per new slot).  NOTE:  Each new video
		is inserted at  the position  shown / declared  in the box
		marked "Number".

	DELETING WITH DEL RELEASED
		When you delete an entry you will blank the selected entry
		(film or video - depending on which operation you click on
		) and the previous  entry will  be selected  ready for the
		next deletion.

	DELETING WITH DEL DEPRESSED
		When you delete an entry the  previous entry will be over-
		-written  by the currently  selected entry  with all  data 
		after the selected one shuffling up behind it.  It's a bit
		like using the backspace key on some text.

   NOTE: Some early demo  versions will not have these features,  although 
	 at the time of writting this the REGISTERED one has them all.

   NOTE: Some areas of the system use Navigation functions differently (to
	 make them more applicable to each areas needs).

   See	@{" Function   " link "Function Menu"} for major functions.
	@{" Set Amend  " link "Amend"} for "Add" mode.
	@{" Set Remove " link "Remove"} for "Del" mode.
@endnode
@node "Function Menu"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Function Menu."

				  @{u}3. FUNCTION MENU@{uu}

				3.1. @{" Amend Film   " link "Amend Film"}
				3.2. @{" Amend Video  " link "Amend Video"}
				3.3. @{" Remove Film  " link "Remove Film"}
				3.4. @{" Remove Video " link "Remove Video"}
				    ------------------
				3.5. @{" Channels     " link "Channels"}
				3.6. @{" Film Types   " link "Film Types"}
				3.7. @{" Owners List  " link "Owners List"}
				3.8. @{" Video Makes  " link "Video Makes"}
@endnode
@node "Amend Film"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Amend Film."

				@{u}3.1 AMEND FILM@{uu}

   This major function can be called up in any one of three ways:-
	Menu	Select Function/"Amend Film" from the pull down menu.
	Icon	Select the film icon with a green plus sign on it (4th row
		up,left most column).
	Select	Clicking left mouse button on any film already selected.

   NOTE: You may only use this button where a video exists (and only if it
	 belongs to you)!

   @{u}Interface@{uu} (Yellow text headings indicate semi-compulsory fields)

   This should be fairly self-explanatory, but here is a list of what each
   field does (starting left to right, top to bottom):-

   QUIT GADGET
	Exits this panel  ignoring any unsubmitted (USEd changes)  leaving
	the user back at the main screen.

   RECORD ADVERTS (top right @{" cycle button " link "Cycle Button"})
	This  button   takes  any @{" channel " link "Channels"}  data  that  concerns  films
	recorded with adverts cut out by the user. This function estimates
	the real  length with data entered in  prefs (percentage tolerance
	of breaks for a length)  and also in the Channel function  (length
	and frequency of adverts for a given channel) and assigns the film
	length accordingly.

	Use of this button can be  a bit of a game if you don't understand
	how it  evaluated.  Basically,  the gadget is  evaluated  when you 
	click on "Use". If you start with a tick and end with a cross then
	the length of a film will contract accordingly.  If you start with
	a cross and end with a tick  then the film will expand in size. At
	the time of writing this, all version have this fiddly system, but
	hopefully (i make no promises),  by the time the first application
	for a REGISTERED cversion arrives this should be improved some!

	If the selected film channel does not use adverts then this option
	is rendered  useless (until such  time as you  allocate  a channel
	with adverts for the film!)

	NB. Lengths are  rounded to  the  nearest  whole  minute  so small
	    anomalies  with the original  lengths will  be present  if the
	    function is repeated to expand a contracted length.

   FILM TITLE (Entry point beneath the "Film Title" text)
	Where the name of the film, program or whatever is entered.

   LP CYCLE GADGET (At right end of "Film Title" entry box)
	This toggles how much room the film take up on the tape:-

		./ Enabled	Long Play (œ of Short Play)
		X  Disabled	Short Play (2x Long Play)

   LENGTH
	This is where you can enter the length of a film / program.  Links
	are internally made to S.TIME and F.TIME such that an entry in any 
	two fields will calculate the third field.

	As with the other  S.TIME and F.TIME  the length may be entered in 
	mmm minute format (eg. "180" for 3 hours).

   DATE
	Here the user may, if he/she wishes,  place the date when the film 
	was recorded.  Please use the format dd.mm.yy  where possible (for
	future compatibility)

   S.TIME
	This is the time at  which the film/program started.  The time can
	be entered in a number of formats:-

	mmm	Minutes			eg. 780		1pm
	hh:mm	24hr 			eg. 14:00	2pm	
	hh.mm	Time AM			eg. 11.00	11am
	hh·mm	Time PM ("·" = Alt+8)	eg. 11·00	11pm

   F.TIME
	This is the time when the film/program finished.  The time formats
	are identical to S.TIME.

   CHANNEL
	This  (and TYPE/CLASS)  consist  of a  scrollable  window which is 
	manipulated  via the slider bar and  1-step arrows to the right of
	the window. Beneath, the currently selected entry is displayed.

	This field is selected using the mouse, representing which channel
	the program was recorded on.  It dictates  whether the  REC ADVERT 
	cycle gadget  may be used  (depending if the channel selected uses
	advert breaks). The @{" channel entries " link "Channels"} may be edited.

   TYPE/CLASS
	This uses a  similar interface to CHANNEL (see above)  and is used
	as an optional  field for  anything the  user has  edited into the 
        @{" type/class " link "Film Types"} field. EG. BFCC Classification, Film types  (action,
        horror..) etc.

   QUIT
	See QUIT GADGET above.

   PREV
	Pulls the previous film into the film editor panel.

   NEXT
	Pulls the next film into the film editor panel.

   USE
	Submits changes, saving them to the current videobase.


   @{u}NOTE@{uu}
	If the "MOBL" button is depressed (Mobile visible in the top right
	of the main screen)  is depressed then you  may edit several films
	(Pressing  "USE" after  each)  before QUITing  the interface.  All
	edits will be copied to the videobase.

   @{u}NOTES ON SENSIBLE OPERATION@{uu}
	You may amend/insert films  upto the slot after the last allocated
	one (ie. If you have 5 allocated films  then only slots 1 to 6 may
	be worked on).  This ensures that films are stored contiguously on
	the tape.

	In short, films 1 to N should have at least the length data field 
	filled, where N is the  penultimate working film  slot available.
	Obviously,  the available working  slots  can be from  one to the
	maximum number of films declared in @{" Pref/Set Options " link "Set Options"}.

	If you like  recording in the  middle of a blank  section then you
	should allocate a  film before the one recorded, giving it no name
	and the  length of the blank area .  I do not advise such reckless
	recording  (it serves to make life harder for yourself both in PVC
	and physically finding a films/programmes position).

   See Also:-
	@{" Editor/Set Amend      " link "Amend"} for "Add" mode.
	@{" Editor/Set A/D Nav    " link "Nav"} for function modifiers.
	@{" Locked & Owned Videos " link "Video RW"}
@endnode
@node "Amend Video"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Amend Video."

				@{u}3.2 AMEND VIDEO@{uu}

   This function  panel allows  you to edit video details.  You may access 
   it by  selecting  Function/"Amend Video"  from the pull  down  menus or 
   clicking on the icon with a black video with a green plus sign on it.
 
   @{u}The Interface@{uu} (Yellow text indicates semi-compulsory entry fields)

   Reading from  left to right, top to bottom  the buttons for  this panel
   are as follows:-

   QUIT GADGET
	Exits  this panel  without  saving  any changes  (except those any
	submitted with VID/ADD buttons when in MOBILE mode).

   LOCK CYCLE GADGET
	Dictates  whether or not  the video and it's contents  can readily 
	changed/deleted: a write protect for video entries. Protect videos
	maybe unprotected by disabling (clicking the cycle gadget until an
	"X" is visible) lock.

   NUMBER 
	This is the video number you wish to make edits for.  On the fully
	REGISTERED version  this may be 0 to 999 (memory permitting).  The
	value always  defaults to  the video that  was in the main display
	you selected the Amend Video function.

   LENGTH	E
	This field is  concerned with the video length.  Nearly all videos 
	state this on their packaging as Ennn  (eg. E180, E210, E240 etc).
	Use the number after the E  -  PVC takes care of Long Play lengths
	on it's own. By the way, you may specify anything from 0 to 499.

   VIDEO MAKE
	This uses a list of @{" company names " link "Video Makes"} that is amended elsewhere. The
	list is  in a  scrollable window  that may  be scrolled using  the
	slider bar  (down the right edge)  or the single increment buttons
	(top  and  bottom  of the  slider bar).  Underneath is  placed the
	currently selected make.

   VIDEO OWNER
	This allows the user to prevent people from editing the video. You
	may also prevent people  from actively  reading entries  by giving
	yourself a @{" password " link "Set Options"} .  Why you'd want/need to do  this is your
	business, but the feature is there if you should.

	On registered version this defaults to the ID currently in use.

	The interface style is identical to VIDEO MAKE (above).

   QUIT
	See QUIT GADGET above.

   VID
	This update button  alters any video details without  clearing any
	film entries that might exist on that video number already.

   ADD
	This button updates any video details, blanking any existing films
	for the video number (see NUMBER above).


   @{u}NOTE@{uu}
	If the "MOBL" button is depressed (Mobile visible in the top right
	of the main screen) is depressed then you  may edit several videos
	(Pressing "VID" or "ADD" after each) before QUITing the interface.
	All edits will be copied to the videobase.

   @{u}NOTE@{uu}
	Any video may be allocated (unlike films they do not have to have 
	slots 1 to n filled with n is the last entry).

   See Also:-
	@{" Editor/Set Amend      " link "Amend"} for "Add" mode.
	@{" Editor/Set A/D Nav    " link "Nav"} for function modifiers.
	@{" Locked & Owned Videos " link "Video RW"}
@endnode
@node "Remove Film"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Remove Film."

				@{u}3.3 REMOVE FILM@{uu}

   By now,  you should understand  how to add a  video and then  (and only
   then) it's films. Now, unless you never make a mistake adding a film on
   the wrong video or never record over your videos, you will surely want
   some way of blanking and/or deleteing entries altogether.

   As i have previously discussed (and will go on to discuss further) you
   can remove a film by selecting the Remove Video button/menu option.

   Obviously, blanking a video is a little drastic if you only want to get
   rid of one film. Thats where this function comes in.

   You may select this function by clicking on the button that looks like
   piece of film with a  red subtract sign on it (4th row up, 3rd column,
   just above the button marked "Del"),  or by selecting Function/"Remove
   Film" from the menu.

   A summary of this buttons various modes follows:-

	@{u}Mode of Operation   	"Del"   	"Mobl"@{uu}

	Blanks				Released	Released
	Back-Blanks			Released	Depressed
	Deletes				Depressed	Released
	Backspaces			Depressed	Depressed

   These four modes of operation are  discussed fully in @{" Set Remove " link "Remove"} & 
   @{" Set A/D Nav " link "Nav"} elsewhere. 

   See Also:-
	@{" Function/Remove Video " link "Remove Video"
	@{" Locked & Owned Videos " link "Video RW"}
@endnode
@node "Remove Video"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Remove Video."

				@{u}3.4 REMOVE VIDEO@{uu}

   This function may be selected by either  clicking on the icon appearing
   as a video with a red subtract sign upon (4th row up, right most column
   just above "Del") or from the menu option Function/"Remove Video".

   Normal operation  involves a click  to clear any  existing films on the
   selected video  and a  second click  (if the video had films on it)  to
   remove the video.

   Removal  of  videos  and  films  are  affected  by  @{" Set Remove " link "Remove"}  and
   @{" Set A/D Nav " link "Nav"} described in full elsewhere. 
  
   A summary of this buttons various modes follows:-

	@{u}Mode of Operation   	"Del"   	"Mobl"@{uu}

	Blanks				Released	Released
	Back-Blanks			Released	Depressed
	Deletes				Depressed	Released
	Backspaces			Depressed	Depressed

   These four modes of operation are  discussed fully in @{" Set Remove " link "Remove"} & 
   @{" Set A/D Nav " link "Nav"} elsewhere. 

   See Also:-
	@{" Locked & Owned Videos " link "Video RW"}
@endnode
@node "Channels"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Channels."

				@{u}3.5 CHANNELS@{uu}

   This function may be selected by either  clicking on the icon appearing
   as the letters "CH" in yellow (5th row up, left most column) or from
   the menu option Function/Channels.

   The operation of the interface is quite simple. Taking each field from 
   right to left, top to bottom we have:-

   QUIT GADGET
	Returns the user to the main interface.  Any changes that have not
	had "Add" or "Del" buttons pressed are ignored. If you are using 
	@{" Mobl " link "Nav"} mode RETURN and DEL keys have  the same response as "Add"
	and "Del" respectfully.

   AD FREQ.
 	This is where  the advert  frequency  (how often adverts  occur on
	average) for a channel is entered. If the channel that is selected
	or in the process of being added (see selection window below) does
	not have adverts leave this field as 0 (default).  Unit = Minutes.
	British terestrial  commercial channels are usually between 20 and
	40 minutes apart  (I use 35 mins - experiment for a happy medium).

   AD LEN.
	The value entered here dictates how long each advert is in minutes.
	In Britain,  the two  terestrial  commercial  channels work  out at
	about 4/5 minutes  on average.  ALWAYS use the lowest value, making
	sure that  the estimate  never over  estimates the  amount of video
	space left.

   SELECTION WINDOW (no heading)
	This uses a list of existing channel slots in a  scrollable window
	that may be scrolled using the slider bar (down the right edge) or
	the single increment buttons (top and  bottom  of the slider bar).
	Underneath is placed the currently selected channel.  Here you may 
	edit the name of the channel  if wished  by clicking  inside it so
	that a  rectangular  cursor is  visible.  Once you  have  finished
	editing it pess RETURN or select "Add".
	
   QUIT
	See QUIT GADGET above.

   DEL
	This button simply blanks the currently selected slot.  If you are
	using @{" Mobile Mode" link "Nav} then the interface  will not vanish at this 
	point, but will select the entry prior to the one deleted. You may
	exit by using the "Quit Gadget", "Quit" or by pressing ESC key.

   ADD
	Once you have changed  the data fields you must press  this button
	(or the RETURN key) to submit changes. At this point the interface 
	will exit normally. If however, you are using Mobile mode then the
	interface will not disappear until you press ESC, select "Quit" or
	click on the  "Quit Gadget".  The selection bar will  move forward
	selecting the next slot. 	


   @{u}BUG ALERT@{uu}
	The bug on DEMO version with  the selector has not been fixed yet!
	It can be  lived with  for now:  just note that  the selection bar
	does not move on properly (even though the selection is made!

	The REGISTERED version feature a corrected selection update.
@endnode
@node "Film Types"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Film Types."

				@{u}3.6 FILM TYPES@{uu}

   This function may be selected by either  clicking on the icon appearing
   as a dagger and tennis racket (5th row up, 2nd column) or from the menu
   option Function/"Film Types".

   This interface gives you complete freedom to classify your films as you
   wish (eg. BFCC certificates, genre, personal ratings etc).

   Taking each field from right to left, top to bottom:-

   QUIT GADGET
	Returns the user to the main interface.  Any changes that have not
	had "Add" or "Del" buttons  pressed are ignored.  If you are using 
	@{" Mobl " link "Nav"} mode RETURN and DEL keys have  the same response as "Add"
	and "Del" respectfully.

   SELECTION WINDOW (no heading)
	This lists all  existing film  type slots  in a scrollable  window
	that may be scrolled using the slider bar (down the right edge) or
	the single increment buttons (top and  bottom  of the slider bar).
	Underneath is  placed the currently selected type. It is here that
	you may edit the film type by clicking inside it, so that a cursor
	becomes visible. Once you have finished editing it press RETURN or
	select "Add".
	
   QUIT
	See QUIT GADGET above.

   DEL
	This button simply blanks the currently selected slot.  If you are
	using @{" Mobile Mode" link "Nav} then the interface  will not vanish at this 
	point, but will select the entry prior to the one deleted. You may
	exit by using the "Quit Gadget", "Quit" or by pressing ESC key.

   ADD
	Once you have changed  the data fields you must press  this button
	(or the RETURN key) to submit changes. At this point the interface 
	will exit normally. If however, you are using Mobile mode then the
	interface will not disappear until you press ESC, select "Quit" or
	click on the  "Quit Gadget".  The selection bar will  move forward
	selecting the next slot. 	


   @{u}BUG ALERT@{uu}
	The bug on DEMO version with  the selector has not been fixed yet!
	It can be  lived with  for now:  just note that  the selection bar
	does not move on properly (even though the selection is made!

	The REGISTERED version feature a corrected selection update.
@endnode
@node "Owners List"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Owners List."

				@{u}3.7 OWNERS LIST@{uu}

   This function may be selected by either  clicking on the icon appearing
   as a  luggage-type  label  (5th row up,  3nd column)  or from  the menu
   option Function/"Film Types".

   This interface allows you to define yourself as a named user of PVC. By
   doing this you prevent people from editing you video data at all. And
   should you want to hide the data altogether you may do so by giving
   yourself a password using @{" Prefs/Set Options " link "Set Options"} .
 
   Taking each field from right to left, top to bottom:-

   QUIT GADGET
	Returns the user to the main interface.  Any changes that have not
	had "Add" or "Del" buttons  pressed are ignored.  If you are using 
	@{" Mobl " link "Nav"} mode RETURN and DEL keys have  the same response as "Add"
	and "Del" respectfully.

   SELECTION WINDOW (no heading)
	This lists  all existing owner  slots in a scrollable  window that
	may be  scrolled using  the slider bar  (down the  right edge)  or
	the single increment buttons (top and  bottom  of the slider bar).
	Underneath is placed the currently selected owner. It is here that
	you may edit blank  owner names by  clicking inside it,  so that a
	cursor becomes visible. Owners may only change their own name. You
	will be alerted to this if the screen flashes (indicating that you
	have accidently  tried to alter/delete  another owners name.  When
	you have finished editing it press RETURN or select "Add".
	
   QUIT
	See QUIT GADGET above.

   DEL
	This button simply blanks the currently selected slot.  If you are
	using @{" Mobile Mode" link "Nav} then the interface  will not vanish at this 
	point, but will select the entry prior to the one deleted. You may
	exit by using the "Quit Gadget", "Quit" or by pressing ESC key.

   ADD
	Once you have changed  the data fields you must press  this button
	(or the RETURN key) to submit changes. At this point the interface 
	will exit normally. If however, you are using Mobile mode then the
	interface will not disappear until you press ESC, select "Quit" or
	click on the  "Quit Gadget".  The selection bar will  move forward
	selecting the next slot. 	


   @{u}BUG ALERT@{uu}
	The bug on DEMO version with  the selector has not been fixed yet!
	It can be  lived with  for now:  just note that  the selection bar
	does not move on properly (even though the selection is made!

	The REGISTERED version feature a corrected selection update.
@endnode
@node "Video Makes"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Video Makes."

				@{u}3.8 VIDEO MAKES@{uu}

   This function may be selected by either  clicking on the icon appearing
   as multi-coloured ball (5th row up, right most column) or from the menu
   option Function/"Video Makes".

   This interface allows  you to define which manufacturer  made the video
   tape in use.  This can make life a lot easier  when finding a tape. You
   can also use this function to identify dodgey video brands when you get
   more fuzz than picture after your first recording. 
 
   Taking each field from right to left, top to bottom:-

   QUIT GADGET
	Returns the user to the main interface.  Any changes that have not
	had "Add" or "Del" buttons  pressed are ignored.  If you are using 
	@{" Mobl " link "Nav"} mode RETURN and DEL keys have  the same response as "Add"
	and "Del" respectfully.

   SELECTION WINDOW (no heading)
	This lists  all existing owner  slots in a scrollable  window that
	may be  scrolled using  the slider bar  (down the  right edge)  or
	the single increment buttons (top and  bottom  of the slider bar).
	Underneath is placed  the currently  selected owner.  Here you may
	amend any video makes  or blank slots by  clicking inside it, such
	that a  cursor  becomes visible.  When you have  finished  editing 
	press RETURN or select "Add".
	
   QUIT
	See QUIT GADGET above.

   DEL
	This button simply blanks the currently selected slot.  If you are
	using @{" Mobile Mode" link "Nav} then the interface  will not vanish at this 
	point, but will select the entry prior to the one deleted. You may
	exit by using the "Quit Gadget", "Quit" or by pressing ESC key.

   ADD
	Once you have changed  the data fields you must press  this button
	(or the RETURN key) to submit changes. At this point the interface 
	will exit normally. If however, you are using Mobile mode then the
	interface will not disappear until you press ESC, select "Quit" or
	click on the  "Quit Gadget".  The selection bar will  move forward
	selecting the next slot. 	


   @{u}BUG ALERT@{uu}
	The bug on DEMO version with  the selector has not been fixed yet!
	It can be  lived with  for now:  just note that  the selection bar
	does not move on properly (even though the selection is made!

	The REGISTERED version feature a corrected selection update.
@endnode
@node "Search Menu"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Search Menu."

				   @{u}@{b}4. SEARCH MENU@{uu}@{ub}

				4.1. @{" Search Query  " link "Search Query"}
				4.2. @{" Find Next     " link "Find Next"}
				4.3. @{" Find Previous " link "Find Previous"}
@endnode
@node "Search Query"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Search Query."

				@{u}4.1 SEARCH QUERY@{uu}

   This is the heart of the search system.  It is here that you define
   exactly what you are searching for.  Click on the button containing a
   single question mark [?], press * on the numeric keypad or select the
   first option under the search menu.

   What will appear will be a panel that looks extremely complex.  This is
   in fact not  the case.  For simplicity  we shall look at this  panel as
   four separate panels (labeled vertically on the real thing) with each
   button/field taken left to right, top to bottom:-

   @{u}TITLE BAR@{uu}

   QUIT GADGET
	Click here (or press ESC key) to quit this interface and return to
	the main interface level.  The data last searched with will not be
	lost,  but  will  be  accessed  again  with  the  @{" Find Next     " link "Find Next"} , 
	@{" Find Previous " link "Find Previous"} or here again.

   DISP. PROGRESS
	This cycle gadget,  when ticked,  shows video/film search progress
	in top box out of the CONTROL PANEL. However, searching is quicker
	without a progress report (set gadget to "X"),  but each  to their 
	own!
	

   @{u}EXTRAS PANEL@{uu}

   V.FREE
	This parameter  dictates how much  minimum  space PVC looks for on
	each video  of the current  videobase.  Any videos with less space
	will be skipped over. Times may take the forms:- 

		mmm	Minutes			eg. 780		1pm
		hh:mm	24hr 			eg. 14:00	2pm	
		hh.mm	Time AM			eg. 11.00	11am
		hh·mm	Time PM ("·" = Alt+8)	eg. 11·00	11pm

   V.USED
	The opposite of the above, this is only used if V.Free is omitted. 

   V.LOCK
	PVC supports  write  protection  of video tapes. This was included
	for a future addition to the PVC tools range. However, it's of use
	for anyone  not wishing  to  accidentally  alter  certain  videos.
	This @{" cycle button " link "Cycle Button"} allows you  to search
	for various protection states. If you aren't interested in whether
	a video  is protected or not,  cycle until a "-" is visible.  This
	indicates a "Don't Care" state (see @{"Cycle Buttons" link "Cycle Button"} .

   F.REC AD
	PVC also supports advert handling.  Some people spend lots of time
	cutting adverts  out of their  recordings,  making it difficult to
	work out exactly  how long a  film is.  PVC attempts  to work this
	gained length out by using data entered with @{" Function/Channels " link "Channels"} .


   @{u}CONTROL PANEL@{uu} (Underneath the Extras panel)
	
   VIDEO
	Don't try to click here. You won't get anything - this box is used
	for displaying search progress only  (See Extras  "Disp. Progress"
	above - tick it for activation).

   FILM
	Same applies here. This displays the  current video being searched
	(don't blink or you'll miss it) only if the Extras "Disp.Progress"
	box has a tick in it.

   SEARCH FROM
	This is a special  form of cycle gadget.  When you click on it the 
	button text will change from "Strt" (Start) to "Defn" (define):-

	STRT	Searches the videobase  from 1 to the last  video checking
		film data for each, where necessary, as it goes.  When the
		last film slot  on the  last video is  reached the  search 
		resumes from video 0 film 1,  continuing the  search until
		the first  position searched  is met.  If a match  is made 
		then the search will select the matched location and exit.
		If  this  is  not  the  case  then  the  last  immediately
		available slot will be selected.

	DEFN	This starts  the search  at the  location  defined  in the 
		"Define" box (below).   The same search  method is applied
		
   DEFN
	When SEARCH FROM shows DEFN, this entry point may be used to input
	which video is searched first.  Searching always  moves up through 
	the videobase,  cycling back  around to 0 when  the last  video is
	reached, continuing until the first video searched is encountered.
	If a match  is found then the search will exit  at the first match
	found. If no matches are found then the search stops and the video
	number defined in the Video Field panels NUMBER box is selected.

   CLR
	Clears all search criteria previously defined.

   USE
	Start  the search  for a video or  film matching  all of  the data 
	defined here (this interface, not this button - Tut!). 

   QUIT
	Return to the main interface without searching.


   @{u}FILM FIELD PANEL@{uu}

   This  panel is the  same as the @{" Amend Film " link "Amend Film"} amend film   panel.  If the following
   is not clear please refer to the amend film section of this document. 

   FILM TITLE
	The name of the film searched for.

   LP
	Is film in Long Play (ticked), Short Play (crossed) or are you not
	interested in it's play speed (dash)?

   LENGTH
	The length of the film you are looking for.

   DATE
	The date the recording was made.

   S.TIME
	The time at which the film started. See below for formats:-

		mmm	Minutes			eg. 780		1pm
		hh:mm	24hr 			eg. 14:00	2pm	
		hh.mm	Time AM			eg. 11.00	11am
		hh·mm	Time PM ("·" = Alt+8)	eg. 11·00	11pm

   F.TIME
	The time  the film finished.  Use the same time  formats as S.TIME
	(above).

   CHANNEL
	The channel the film was recorded on.

   TYPE/CLASS
	Miscellaneous description of the film (eg. Horror, BFCC cert etc).


   @{u}VIDEO FIELD PANEL@{uu}

   This panel is identical to that used to @{" Amend Videos " link "Amend Video"} . Please refer
   to that section  if you are still unsure of what each field means after
   reading the following.

   NUMBER
	The video number you wish to jump  to if no matches are found when
	searching. This function only works if you search from here. Using
	search on demo versions does not use this feature at all (although
	the box is still present).

   LENGTH
	The length of the video as marked on the videos sleeve (eg. E180).

   VIDEO MAKE
	The brand of video searched for (eg. Scotch, TDK, Maxell etc.)

   VIDEO OWNER
	The video ownership searched for. Note, although a search may give
	results of a search using this field  it does not mean you will be
	allowed to see any  of the videos contents if the video is secured
	(see @{" Owned & Locked Videos " link "Video RW"} ).


   @{u}SELECTION WINDOWS@{uu}
	Selection windows have been described elsewhere (try @{" Amend Film " link "Amend Film"}
	for starters).  However,  all of the ones here  have an additional
	cycle  gadget  on the  item  selected  display line.  This enables
	(tick) / disables (cross)  the selection  made to  become  (or not
	become)	a part of the search. If you mean to use the selected item
	as a part of the search make sure it has a tick next to it!  
@endnode
@node "Find Next"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Find Next."

				@{u}4.2 FIND NEXT@{uu}

   This function  is selected  by clicking on  the fast forward type arrow   
   ( » ),  the second  option under the  search menu  or with  "/"  on the
   numeric keypad.

   Basically,  this function allows you to continue searching for any data
   defined in the @{" Search Query " link "Search Query"} interface.
@endnode
@node "Find Prev"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Find Prev."

				@{u}4.3 FIND PREV@{uu}

   This function  is selected  by clicking on the rewind type arrow ( « ),
   the second  option under the  search menu  or with  "/"  on the numeric
   keypad.

   Basically,  this function allows you to continue searching for any data
   defined in  the @{" Search Query " link "Search Query"} search query   interface  previous  to the  currently
   selected position  (the video  in view  and the film  selected)  in the
   videobase.

   That's it really.
@endnode
@node "Prefs Menu"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Preferences Menu."

				    @{b}@{u}5. PREFS MENU@{uu}@{ub}

			   5.1. @{" Set Options         " link "Set Options"}	(Not Demo)
			   5.2. @{" Select Identity     " link "Select ID"}	(Not Demo)
			       -------------------------
			   5.3. @{" Load Default Config " link "Load Defaults"}	(Not Demo)
			   5.4. @{" Save Default Config " link "Save Defaults"}	(Not Demo)
			       -------------------------
			   5.5. @{" Load Config         " link "Load Config"}	(Not Demo)
			   5.6. @{" Save Config         " link "Save Config"}	(Not Demo)
@endnode
@node "Set Options"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Set Options."

			     @{u}5.2 SET OPTIONS@{uu}

   This panel is used to configure PVC.  It may only be  selected from the
   pull down menus  (Prefs/"Set Options").  Taking each panel in  turn and
   their contents from left to right, we have:-

   @{u}MEM PANEL@{uu}

   This panel defines how big the videobase and misc data stores are.

   LAST VIDEO NO.
	This  box is  where the  last  video  number  in the  videobase is
	defined. The value may not be greater than 999.

   LAST FILM NO.
	It is here  that the number  of films per  video is defined.  This
	value should be kept a small as reasonably possible (about 10 - 15
	is a good start). Remember, you can always alter this figure, save
	the changes as the  default config  and re-load PVC if you run out
	of room.  Keeping the  videobase size  under  control is a  way of
	making it behave under tight memory restrictions.

   LAST MISC NO.
	This value defines the number of video owners and makes as well as
	the number of film types and channels.  The maximum is 26 and, for
	the most part, it need never be set less.


   @{u}SYSTEM PANEL@{uu}

   This panel  replaces  the need  to assign PVC: .  Both have manual text 
   entry boxes, and to the left  "SEL" buttons  which allow  you to define
   the same data as you might type via the file selector.

   PVC PATH
	This is where PVC  looks for this guide,  the news file (if one is
	available)  and other bit's and bobs  that may become available in 
	future versions (but probably won't *GRIN*)

   DATA FILENAME
	If you  use one  videobase  often,  you might like  to load  it as
	default it by entering it's name and it's path. All videobase file
	operations should default to this path.


   @{u}INFO PANEL@{uu}

   This allows PVC PATH overrides for this and other documentation as well
   as your prefered  AmigaGuideź  viewer and  it's path.  See SYSTEM PANEL
   foreword concerning this type of interface.

   HELP FILENAME
	This can contain the path and name of this help file  (which isn't
	compulsory on REGISTERED versions).

   NEWS FILENAME
	Updates to PVC (as and when they appear) will contain a News file.
	This box and button allow you to  define where and under what name
	you wish to store it as (as if the default isn't good enough!).

   TEXT VIEWER
	PVC isn't very good at viewing AmigaGuide files on it's own  (like
	AMOS Pro really).  Instead,  PVC allows you  to select  a suitable 
	viewing  system that  you may  flip to  using Left  Amiga and  "A"
	together.  OS3.x owners (like myself) will  have Multiview.  Other 
	persons should download the AmigaGuide distribution available from
	all good ftp sites (AmiNet at anyway) and PD libraries. At worst
	you could muddle through with a text viewer such as More.

	Anyway, point is, this button allows you to define what viewer can
	be used and where it is located.


   @{u}GO PANEL@{uu}

   This button is used when you have finished configuring PVC. I know that
   I should mention this last, but it's the next panel down *sigh*.

   QUIT
	This button quits the configuration, forgetting any changes made.

   USE
	Press this button  to enable all changes.  However,  this will not
	save them. For that you should see:-

			@{" Save Default Config " link "Save Defaults"}
		   	@{" Save Config         " link "Save Config"}	


   @{u}MISC PANEL@{uu}

   This panel is used  to define various useful bits 'n' bobs!  (There's a
   general statement if ever there were one!)

   VIDEO LENGTH
	This allows you to define the default video length.  So if you use
	E180 videos most  of the time you  should set  this to 180 to save
	you blessed little fingers from wearing away.

   ADVERT LENGTH
	Useful if the comercial channels all waste the same amount of time
	selling lawn mowers and the like  to 3 year olds  (the only people 
	that seem to  be influenced by them).  When amending a channel the
	value defined here will save typing in the "AD LEN" field.

   ADVERT FREQ TOL (Advert Frequency Tolerance)
	Basically, the value here is the percentage increase/decrease that
	is used  to define whether  a slot has n adverts  or n+1  adverts.
	It's hard to explain without getting technical,  but to illustrate
	the use  of this value  better,  let's make  some assumptions  and 
	work out roughly what this value should reasonably be:-

	Advert Frequency 		= 30
	Advert Frequency Tolerance 	= 33 (percent)

	With these values  a program of 40 minutes would  have have only 1
	advert  break and not 2.  A film of 85 would  have 3 breaks like a
	film of 90 minutes and not 2 breaks like a 60 minute film. 

	The best thing to obtain an  understanding is expe riment with the
	value. Remember it is a percentage increase/decrease.


   @{u}G/SFX@{uu}
	This concerns the aesthetics of PVC.

   MUSIC/SFX
	This comprises of the text box, "SEL" file selector button and the
	cycle gadget  labelled "Sound".  The cycle gadget  defines whether 
	anything will be heard from PVC (set it to a cross for no sound at
	all).

	If "Sound" cycle gadget contains a tick then sound will be audible
	be it music of spot effects.  Which of these is defined by whether
	the protracker module defined in the text box exists (you can name
	one by typing the path and  file names into the box or by clicking
	on "sel" and  selecting a file  from the  file requester).  If the 
	module does not exist then sound effects will be played, otherwise
	it's spot effects for you.

   BLANK TIME
	PVC has it's  own screen blanker that dims  the screen after there 
	has been no input from the user  for the number of seconds defined 
	here. 0 switches blanking off altogether.


   @{u}OUT@{uu}

   This panel defines how data is output.

   TAG DATA
	This is the "Auto videobase comment inheritance tagging" mentioned
	in the registration details.  Basically, any comments added to the
	videobase saves before the <SOF> marker  or after the <EOF> marker
	are maintained  in future saves  if there is a tick in  this cycle
	gadget. If not then such comments are not inherited between video-
	-base saves.

   ENCRYPT
	This adds a level of security to the saved data. The whole save is
	encrypted, with any passworded users recieving a second encryption
	based on their password.

	This doesn't come cheap though.  Amos has a serious  problem doing
	what is  essentially quite a  simple task  in anything faster than
	a Network SouthEast  train in autumn  (leaves on the  track pah!).
	IE. This means SLOOOOOWWW file loading, merging and saving.  Makes
	for time to make a cup-a-tea...


   @{u}SECURITY@{uu}

   This area is dedicated to making password changes. You must fill in all
   of the text boxes in this panel to achieve a change of password.

   OLD PASSWORD
	Type in your  old password here if you have one.  If no just press
	the RETURN key (ie. enter a blank entry).

   NEW PASSWORD
	Now type in your new password carefully in this text box.

   VERIFY PASSWORD
	And finally type in your new password again in this text box.

   If the old password matches the one your current ID has and the new and
   verify passwords are the same, your password will be changed.  If, when
   you press RETURN in  the verify text box,  any of the data is incorrect
   the screen will flash.

   NOTE: Demo version will  stay a funny colour.  This was an old bug that
         stayed hidden for a long time (Bryan said nothing to me about it)
	 but has been fixed in the REGISTERED version.
@endnode
@node "Select ID"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Select Identity."

			     @{u}5.2 SELECT IDENTITY@{uu}

   This function is designed to allows  users to move from one named owner
   to another, provided they know the password (if any is defined) for the
   selected owner name, without the need to reload the videobase.

   Putting it simply,  you can have more  than one id  (public & private?)
   and control who sees the contents of your video collection.

   The interface is identical in both appearence and operation to the one
   used for @{" Security Checks " link "Security Checks"}
@endnode
@node "Load Defaults"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Load Default Config."

			     @{u}5.3 LOAD DEFAULT CONFIG@{uu}

   This loads the default configuration/preferences file:-

				    S:PVC.prefs

   All data  stored  therein  will  become active  immediately,  with  the 
   exception of Last Video, Last Film and Last Misc parameters.

   The file format used is compatible with all of the other file operators
   under the @{" Preferences Menu " link "Prefs Menu"} menu heading.
@endnode
@node "Save Defaults"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Save Default Config."

			     @{u}5.4 SAVE DEFAULT CONFIG@{uu}

   This menu option saves the current system configuration and preferences
   to the file:-
				    S:PVC.prefs

   The file format  is fully compatible with  the other configuration file
   operators under the @{" Preferences Menu " link "Prefs Menu"} menu heading.
@endnode
@node "Load Config"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Load Config."

				  @{u}5.5 LOAD CONFIG@{uu}

   This option  loads  up any pre-defined  configuration (preference) file
   created  by using  the @{" Save Default Config " link "Save Defaults"} or the @{" Save Config " link "Save Config"}
   options under the @{" Preferences Menu " link "Prefs Menu"} .

   All options  within the said file  will become immediately active  with
   the exception of any functions coming under MEM(ory management).  These
   are   Last  Video,   Last  Film  and  Last  Misc  options  as  seen  in 
   @{" Set Options " link "Set Options"} panel and as LASTVIDEO, LASTFILM and LASTMISC constructs
   in the actual file.

   Load  Config uses the standard  AMOS Pro  file requestor and  should be
   fairly self explanatory. 
@endnode
@node "Save Config"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Save Config."

				  @{u}5.6 SAVE CONFIG@{uu}

   This  option  save  the current  system  configuration  and  preference 
   settings   as   defined   in   the @{" Set  Options " link "Set Options"} panel   under   the 
   @{" Prefereces Menu " link "Prefs Menu"} .

   All options are saved in the same format as the @{" Save Default Config " link "Save Defaults"}
   under the same menu and thereby, making both files 100% compatible.

   Save  Config uses the standard  AMOS Pro  file requestor and ishould be
   faily self explanatory. 
@endnode
@node "Docs Menu"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Docs Menu."

				    @{b}@{u}6. DOCS MENU@{uu}@{ub}

				6.1. @{" External Help " link "This Help"}
				6.2. @{" External News " link "News File"}	(Not Demo) 
@endnode
@node "This Help"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: External Help."

				   @{u}6.1 EXTERNAL HELP@{uu}

   The "Help" part of the name refers to this document. 

   The "External" part is a little  more complicated.  As you will already
   know, this  documentation is  in the  AmigaGuideź  format and  requires
   MultiView  to read it  (or the AmigaGuide  distribution  for WB2.04 and
   below). So to save any legal problems PVC calls any text viewer or your
   choice   (except   on   the   demo   in   which   case   it  hunts  for
   SYS:Utilities/Multiview).  If it can't find this  then PVC will  use an
   internal text viewer.
@endnode
@node "News File"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: External News."

				   @{u}6.2 EXTERNAL NEWS@{uu}

   This document works exactly the same way as the @{" External Help " link "This Help"} , but
   unlike it, it is only available to REGISTERED users. 

   So whats it all about?  Well, it's generally an opening for new product
   announcements.  It is unlikely that there is anything new in there of
   any such announcements until after Christmas'93.

   Read it anyway.. just to be sure though! (O8*?
@endnode
@node "Support"
@title "AmigaGuideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Support"

				@{b}@{u}F. SUPPORT@{uu}@{ub}

   At the time writting, PVC is  under Beta test.  With any luck none will
   escape my self or Bryan "Fraggle" Baigent. However, PVC is well equiped
   for bug reporting.  In the event of  the program  failing a window will
   appear (unless the error is fatal) giving you an SDF$(xx) code. Simply,
   make a note of what you were doing at the time (eg adding a film called 
   "BuG!",with a length of 090 SP, on channel... (you get the idea)), what
   machine  configuration  you  have  (CPU, memory, OS  etc) and  that all
   important  SDF$(xx) code.  Mail this  to the  address given  earlier or
   email it to:-

		InterNet:  s5002298@brookes.ac.uk

   If you use email, mail me a copy of the videobase you were using at the 
   time. The more comprehensive your report the more chance there is of me
   finding the little bleeder (er .. bug).
@endnode
@node "History"
@title "Amiga Guideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: History"

				@{b}@{u}G. HISTORY@{uu}@{ub}
	
   Nov'92	Initial  designs for ProVIDence (sequential fore-runner of
                PVC).
   Dec'92	Coding started and continued for the next month or so.
   Feb'93	ProVIDence abandoned as it was too  slow from floppy. Most
		of ProVIDence's code was transferred to a new system...
   Mar'93	PVC v0.0 completed. No interface, simple add, del, search.
   Jun'93	PVC v0.1  finished.   Major  functions  in place  and  90%
		operational.
   Sept'93	Security features  added to  PVC v0.4 (v0.2 and  v0.3 were
		mostly bug fixes with a few code optimisations).
   Oct'93	PVC v0.5 completed. Preference system added.
   Nov'93	PVC v0.6. Added printer options + a number of bug fixes.
		(Planned release on 11th v1.0e/rß bugs found and
		documentations not completed - decided to hold off).
   Dec'93	Minor improvements to efficiency.
   Jan'94	Minor bug fixes.  Improvements to  documentation.  Further
		improvements to PVC "Mobl" mode. Ownership bug fixed as is 
		the alert ownership flash (silly mistake).
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 18th Jan'94	First (limited) public release. Known bugs:  The misc data
		interfaces seem to have a problem with the last entry. I'm
		hoping to have this sorted out shortly.
@endnode
@node "Apology"
@title "Amiga Guideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Apology time."

				@{u}Sorry for any Delays@{uu}

	PVC has taken it's sweet time in making it to full release. Most
	problems weren't with actually coding, but with finding the time
	amid my other commitments.

	Unfortunately this meant  that the initial  release date slipped
	and slipped.  I would like to thank  members of the AMOS mailing
	list (amos-list@net.digex.access) for their patience as this was
	where the initial release date was placed. 

	Some bugs still exist, but I haven't got enough time to fix them
	just yet.  Still, by the  time the first  person registers  they
	will hopefully have been sprayed *GRIN*

	Better late than never...

	T.L.Bullock (S5002298@brookes.ac.uk)
@endnode
@node "Future"
@title "Amiga Guideź. Professional Video Catalogue ©1993: Future"

				@{b}@{u}H. FUTURE@{uu}@{ub}

   The future of Professional Video Catalogue is  inextricably linked with 
   how successful the registered version sells.  Currently there are plans
   to release a number of  tools (all of  which under design currently and
   all very cloak-and-dagger at the moment).

   These may be added as enhancements to PVC  or as a separate tools pack. 
   This depends mostly on whether  EuroPress  release an AMOS Professional 
   Compiler with a 2-pass compile option (thus producing object code close
   to other compiled languages such  as Pascal, C and Modula-2 in terms of 
   size and execution speeds). 

   There are also plans for improving  the current system in general, most
   of which are concerned with how  videobase data  is stored and utilised
   to give you, the user, a flexible  system  that will run  on all Amigas 
   reguardless of if  it's a 512k machine  or an 8Mb one.  Detailed  plans
   are  in place using  knowledge  gleaned from other languages.  I'm just
   waiting for Europress... (so I  wouldn't  hold your  breath  if I  were
   you!)

   Acid Softwares Blitz BASIC 2 looks like an alternative that will enable
   all of  the tools  and  future  enhancements  I  intend to  add.  So if
   Europress keep holding me up I may just convert it all over!

   I think I must point  out though that  any plans for PVC are just that.
   They are not  definite commitments  (even though i have drawn up specs,
   file structures and  general new  features already).  It all depends on
   how much free time i can find to pursue this, my hobby.
@endnode
